go encounters for the present-day political status of native people in California.Lightfoot weaves the results of his own significant archaeological research at Fort Ross, a major Russian mercantile colony, into a cross-cultural comparison, showing how these two colonial ventures—one primarily mercantile and one primarily religious—contributed to the development of new kinds of native identities, social forms, and tribal relationships. His lively account includes personal anecdotes from the field and a provocative discussion of the role played by early ethnographers, such as Alfred Kroeber, in influencing which tribes would eventually receive federal recognition. Indians, Missionaries, and Merchants takes a fascinating, yet troubling, look at California’s past and its role in shaping the state today.  aMode of access: Internet via World Wide Web.  aIn English.0 aDescription based on online resource; title from PDF title page (publisher's Web site, viewed 29. Mai 2023) 0aFederal aid to IndianszCalifornia. 0aFederally recognized Indian tribeszCalifornia. 0aIndians of North AmericaxCommercezCaliforniaxHistory. 0aIndians of North AmericaxFirst contact with EuropeanszCalifornia. 0aIndians of North AmericaxFirst contact with other peopleszCalifornia. 0aIndians of North AmericaxMissionszCaliforniaxHistory. 7aSOCIAL SCIENCE / Anthropology / Cultural & Social.2bisacsh  aalfred kroeber.  aamerican colonialism.  aamerican history.  aarchaeology.  acalifornia.  acalifornian history.  acolonial systems.  acolonialism.  aethnography.  aethnohistory.  afort ross.  ahistorical anthropology.  ahistorical.  ahistory.  aindigenous peoples.  alabor.  anative americans.  anative cultures.  anative identity.  anative peoples.  aoral history.  apolitical.  areligion.  aretrospective.  arussian mercantile colony.  arussian merchants.  asocial formations.  aspanish missionaries.  aunited states of ame